nited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Malta","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Carmela, Luigi, Palma, Sal, Vito.  Spanish Alejandro, Luis, Luz, Mercedes, Ramon, Santiago.","Italian (southern), Spanish, and Portuguese: habitational or ethnic name for someone from the Mediterranean island of Malta (from Latin <i>Melita</i>, Greek <i>Melitē</i>).","Dutch: habitational name from any of the places called Malt(h)a, in the Netherlands, named after the Mediterranean island of Malta."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Laas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heino, Otto.","East German: habitational name from a town so named in Saxony, from Slavic <i>laz</i> ‘uncultivated land, clearing’.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Nikolaus  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lass","meanings":["North German: variant of   Laas  .","German: from a short form of   Lorenz  , or a nickname from Middle Low German <i>las, lasch</i> ‘tired, weak’, Middle High German <i>laʒ</i> ‘indolent’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Las  ."]},{"name":"Nikolaus","meanings":["German: from a German form of the Latin personal name <i>Nicolaus</i>, Greek <i>Nikolaos</i> (see   Nicholas  ). After <i>Johann</i> and <i>Peter</i>, <i>Nikolaus</i> was the third most popular personal name in medieval Germany."]}]},{"name":"Wilhelm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>wil</i> ‘will’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet’; an ancient royal name.  See also  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"IV.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Wilhelm IV. von Malta Laas was born in 1207 as the son of Gero II von Heunburg and Elisabeth von Ortenburg. He married * Elizabeth of HIRSCHER-KRONSTADT. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 22 March 1249, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1207–22 March 1249":"1207–22. m